CGR measures growth two time points \(0\) \(T\), pace population growth specific point time \(0 < t < T\)?Define period length \(\Delta t\)Population change \(N(t + \Delta t) - N(t) = \Delta N(t)\)11Person-years lived now \(N(t)\Delta t\)12So crude growth rate now \(r(t) = \frac{\Delta N(t)}{N(t) \Delta t}\)KEY CONCEPTInstantaneous growth rate essentially crude growth rate tiny period length \(\Delta t \rightarrow 0\)Mathematically13:\[\begin{equation}
  r(t) = \lim_{\Delta t \0} \frac{\Delta N(t)}{N(t) \Delta t}
       =\frac{d \text{ln}\left[N(t)\right]}{dt}
  \tag{1.1}
\end{equation}\]can algebra using Equation (1.1) express instantaneous growth accumulates times \(0\) \(T\)14:\[\begin{equation}
  \frac{N(T)}{N(0)} = e^{\int_0^T r(t)dt}
  \tag{1.2}
\end{equation}\]Left-hand side: Ratio ending starting population sizeRight-hand side: Expression cumulative growthRe-arranging:\[\begin{equation}
  N(T) = N(0)e^{\int_0^T r(t)dt}
  \tag{1.3}
\end{equation}\]Assuming constant growth rate \(r^*\)15:\[\begin{equation}
  N(T) = N(0)e^{r^{*} T}
  \tag{1.4}
\end{equation}\]Dividing sides starting population \(N(0)\), see get expression cumulative growth times \(0\) \(T\) constant rate \(r^*\):\[\begin{equation}
  \frac{N(T)}{N(0)} = e^{r^* T}
  \tag{1.5}
\end{equation}\]Exponentiating sides Equation (1.5) dividing \(T\) gives us constant growth rate \(r^*\) effect times \(0\) \(T\):\[\begin{equation}
  r^{*} = \frac{\text{ln} \left[\frac{N(T)}{N(0)}\right]}{T}
  \tag{1.6}
\end{equation}\]

exponentiate sides (1.2) divided \(T\), get:\[
  \frac{\int_0^T r(t)dt}{T} = \frac{\text{ln} \left[\frac{N(T)}{N(0)}\right]}{T}
\]left-hand side just mean growth rate \(\bar{r}[0,T]\), :\[\begin{equation}
  \bar{r}[0,T] = \frac{\text{ln} \left[\frac{N(T)}{N(0)}\right]}{T}
  \tag{1.7}
\end{equation}\]left-hand side known mean annualized growth rate.

\(CDR = \overline{r}\) growth rate constant? Let‚Äôs examine three scenarios: early growth, late growth, constant growth.Look picture :Fig 1.2 PHG. Three scenarios within-period growthStarting ending population sizes \(N(0)\) \(N(T)\) sameThus numerators crude growth rates \(N(0) - N(T)\) sameYet person years (areas curves) definitely aren‚Äôt ! :\[PY[0,T]_{\text{early growth}} \neq PY[0,T]_{\text{late growth}} \neq PY[0,T]_{\text{constant growth}}\]Therefore crude growth rates won‚Äôt equal either, :\[
\frac{N(0) - N(T)}{PY[0,T]_{\text{early growth}}}
\neq \frac{N(0) - N(T)}{PY[0,T]_{\text{late growth}}}
\neq \frac{N(0) - N(T)}{PY[0,T]_{\text{constant growth}}}
= r^*
\]constant growth rate \(r^*[0,T]\), person-years lived :\[
\require{cancel}
PY[0,T]_{\text{constant growth}} = \frac{N(T) - N(0)}{r^*}
\]Thus CGR \(r^*[0,1]\) :\[
CGR[0,T]
  = \frac{N(T) - N(0)}{\left[\frac{N(T) - N(0)}{r^*}\right]}
  = \left[\bcancel{N(T) - N(0)}\right]
  \cdot \frac{r^*}{\bcancel{N(T) - N(0)}}
  = r^*
\]Meanwhile, \(r^*[0,1]\):\[
\overline{r}[0,T] = \frac{1}{T}\int_0^Tr^*dt=r^*
\]KEY CONCEPTWith exceptions, crude growth rate mean annualized growth rate equal unless constant growth rate \(r^*\).

